1. What is an OpenShift Template
Concept
An OpenShift Template is a custom Kubernetes resource that contains multiple Kubernetes objects packaged together.
It allows you to deploy a complete application with dependencies in one step.
A template may create:
•	Deployments / StatefulSets
•	Services
•	Secrets
•	ConfigMaps
•	Routes
•	Persistent Volumes
Instead of creating each resource manually, a template automatically creates all required resources.
________________________________________
Example Scenario
Imagine deploying a web application that needs:
•	database
•	secret
•	service
•	deployment
Without template:
create secret
create deployment
create service
create route
With template:
process template → deploy everything
________________________________________
2. Key Features of Templates
1️⃣ Parameters
Templates support parameters that allow customization during deployment.
Example parameters:
APP_NAME
IMAGE
DATABASE_USER
DATABASE_PASSWORD
These parameters allow the same template to be reused with different values.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Labels
Templates can apply labels automatically to all resources.
Example label:
template=cache-service
This helps with:
•	grouping resources
•	filtering resources
•	monitoring
________________________________________
3️⃣ Object List
A template defines a list of resources it creates.
Example:
Secret
Service
Service
StatefulSet
________________________________________
3. Where Templates Are Stored
Default templates are installed by the:
Cluster Samples Operator
They are stored in the:
openshift namespace
________________________________________
List Available Templates
Command:
oc get templates -n openshift
Example output:
NAME                      DESCRIPTION
cache-service             Red Hat Data Grid
cakephp-mysql-example     Example PHP + MySQL app
This shows:
Column	Meaning
NAME	template name
DESCRIPTION	what it deploys
PARAMETERS	number of parameters
OBJECTS	number of resources created
________________________________________
4. Inspect a Template
To understand what a template does:
oc describe template cache-service -n openshift
This shows:
•	description
•	parameters
•	labels
•	objects created
Example information:
Parameters:
APPLICATION_NAME
APPLICATION_PASSWORD
________________________________________
Generated Parameters
Some parameters are auto-generated.
Example:
APPLICATION_PASSWORD
Generated: expression
From: [a-zA-Z0-9]{16}
This means OpenShift generates a random 16 character password.
________________________________________
5. View Only Template Parameters
Command:
oc process --parameters cache-service -n openshift
Output example:
NAME                   VALUE
APPLICATION_NAME       cache-service
IMAGE                  registry.redhat.io/...
NUMBER_OF_INSTANCES    1
This shows parameters without displaying full template details.
________________________________________
6. View Template YAML
You can see the full template definition.
Command:
oc get template cache-service -o yaml -n openshift
Example structure:
apiVersion: template.openshift.io/v1
kind: Template

parameters:
- name: APPLICATION_NAME
  value: cache-service

objects:
- kind: Secret
- kind: Service
- kind: StatefulSet
Sections:
Section	Meaning
apiVersion	template API
kind	Template
parameters	configurable variables
objects	resources created
________________________________________
7. Deploy an Application from Template
To instantiate a template (create resources from it):
Command
oc new-app --template=cache-service -p APPLICATION_USER=my-user
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
oc new-app	create new application
--template	specify template
-p	set parameter
________________________________________
Example:
APPLICATION_USER=my-user
Overrides default parameter value.
________________________________________
8. Production Method (Recommended)
Instead of using oc new-app, production environments use:
oc process + oc apply
Why?
Because this allows:
•	version control
•	change tracking
•	automation
________________________________________
9. Process a Template
oc process converts a template into normal Kubernetes resources.
Example:
oc process my-cache-service \
-p APPLICATION_USER=user1 \
-o yaml > manifest.yaml
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
oc process	process template
-p	parameter value
-o yaml	output format
>	save to file
Result:
manifest.yaml
contains:
Deployment
Service
Secret
________________________________________
10. Process Template From File
If template is stored locally:
oc process -f my-template.yaml -p USER=user1
________________________________________
11. Use a Parameters File
Instead of writing many parameters in command line, use a parameter file.
Example:
my-cache-service-params.env
File content:
TOTAL_CONTAINER_MEM=1024
APPLICATION_USER=cache-user
APPLICATION_PASSWORD=my-secret-password
Run:
oc process my-cache-service \
--param-file=my-cache-service-params.env \
-o yaml
Advantages:
•	cleaner command
•	easier automation
•	version control
________________________________________
12. Deploy Processed Resources
You can pipe the output directly to oc apply.
Example:
oc process my-cache-service \
--param-file=params.env | oc apply -f -
Explanation:
Command	Purpose
oc process	generate manifests
	(pipe)
oc apply	create/update resources
-f - means read input from pipe.
________________________________________
13. Updating Applications
Templates can be updated by:
1️⃣ Changing parameter file
2️⃣ Processing template again
3️⃣ Applying changes
Example:
oc process my-cache-service \
--param-file=params2.env | oc apply -f -
________________________________________
14. Preview Changes
Before applying updates use:
oc diff
Example:
oc process my-cache-service \
--param-file=params2.env | oc diff -f -
Example output:
- memory: 1Gi
+ memory: 2Gi
Meaning:
Memory changed from 1Gi → 2Gi.
________________________________________
15. Managing Templates
Best practice for production:
Do NOT directly use templates from the openshift namespace.
Instead:
1️⃣ Copy template
2️⃣ Modify parameters
3️⃣ Store in your project
________________________________________
Copy Template
oc get template cache-service \
-o yaml -n openshift > my-cache-service.yaml
________________________________________
Recommended Changes
Modify the template file:
1️⃣ Change template name
name: my-cache-service
2️⃣ Change default parameters
value: custom-value
3️⃣ Remove namespace field
namespace: openshift
________________________________________
16. Upload Template to Project
Command:
oc create -f my-cache-service.yaml
This does NOT create resources.
It only creates a template resource.
________________________________________
Upload to Another Namespace
Example:
oc create -f my-cache-service.yaml -n shared-templates
________________________________________
17. View Templates in Project
oc get templates
Example:
NAME              PARAMETERS   OBJECTS
my-cache-service  8            4
________________________________________
18. Template Deployment Workflow (Real Production)
Typical workflow:
1️⃣ Copy template
oc get template cache-service -n openshift
2️⃣ Customize template
my-cache-service.yaml
3️⃣ Upload template
oc create -f my-cache-service.yaml
4️⃣ Create parameters file
params.env
5️⃣ Deploy application
oc process my-cache-service --param-file=params.env | oc apply -f -
________________________________________
19. Templates vs Helm Charts
Feature	Templates	Helm
Complex apps	Limited	Excellent
Versioning	No	Yes
Package manager	No	Yes
Recommended for	simple apps	complex apps
Because of this, Helm charts are more commonly used today.
